03:09.000 --> 03:11.000
Communication

03:12.000 --> 03:28.000
Communication is a process in which two or more people exchange and realize the received information.

03:29.000 --> 03:34.000
The purpose of the process is to motivate a certain behavior or influence it.

03:34.000 --> 03:43.000
From the general management course, you know that Henry Mintzberg has identified 10 managerial roles that a manager plays in his workplace.

03:44.000 --> 03:47.000
Let's take a closer look at the information role of a manager.

03:48.000 --> 03:51.000
A manager can act as a recipient of information.

03:52.000 --> 04:03.000
He searches and receives information of a specialized nature, which, understanding the organization and external conditions, is successfully used in the interests of his business.

04:04.000 --> 04:09.000
He acts as a kind of center of external and internal information that comes to the organization.

04:10.000 --> 04:19.000
He processes all the mail, makes contacts related to the receipt of information, for example, reads periodic publications or goes on introductory trips.

04:20.000 --> 04:28.000
As a distributor of information, he transmits the information received from external sources or from other subordinates to the members of the organization.

04:28.000 --> 04:37.000
Some of this information is purely factual, while others require interpretation of certain facts to form the organization's views.

04:38.000 --> 04:43.000
Mail sending to organizations in order to provide information is his job.

04:44.000 --> 04:50.000
He also makes verbal contacts with members of the organization to clarify some information.

04:50.000 --> 05:00.000
A manager, as a representative, transmits information to external contacts in the organization regarding plans, policies, actions, results of the organization's work.

05:01.000 --> 05:03.000
He acts as an expert on the issues of this industry.

05:04.000 --> 05:14.000
He participates in meetings, in emails, perhaps, makes oral speeches, including information transmission to external organizations.

05:15.000 --> 05:23.000
Note that both interpersonal roles and roles related to decision-making also require active communication from the manager.

05:24.000 --> 05:32.000
Considering communication in business as a scientific applied discipline also determines the approach, point of view on the processes in business.

05:33.000 --> 05:44.000
We can talk about the so-called communicative approach in management, when the organization considers, first of all, how the relationship between people, between groups.

05:45.000 --> 05:58.000
For example, from the point of view of the communicative approach, management of personnel is an organization of communication related to the activities of individual people and groups in the interests of the organization and in their own interests.

05:58.000 --> 06:12.000
For example, marketing is the communication of the organization with market objects regarding the determination of market needs and the possibility of their satisfaction, or about the means and ways of promoting goods and services of the organization to the market.

06:13.000 --> 06:19.000
Conflictology is the study of communication, based on which the contradictions of the interests of the parties lie.

06:20.000 --> 06:29.000
From the point of view of communication with the public, it is the study of the problem of forming a positive idea of the organization, of its products, of its services.

06:30.000 --> 06:39.000
From the point of view of advertising, it is communication with the aim of attracting attention, forming interest, desire, activity of the buyers of goods.

06:40.000 --> 06:51.000
From the point of view of corporate culture, it is an important component of the culture, it is communication. In fact, corporate culture is a culture of communication, a culture of management.

06:52.000 --> 07:05.000
Communication penetrates all management functions. For example, what is planning? It is a collection of information, writing, notes, reports. It is a meeting with colleagues and managers, an explanation of their plans.

07:06.000 --> 07:17.000
When a manager acts as a leader, he must communicate with his subordinates to motivate them to work. When he is in control, he is also obliged to collect information.

07:18.000 --> 07:26.000
It is because the exchange of information is built into all the basic types of management activity, we call communication a connecting process.

07:26.000 --> 07:30.000
The typology of business communication is presented on slide 11.

07:31.000 --> 07:45.000
Communication is a process associated with interpersonal and organizational communication when transferring information both inside the organization and from the external environment. Therefore, communication can be divided into external and internal.

07:46.000 --> 08:02.000
The factors of the external environment, such as consumers, suppliers, competitors, determine the composition and content of external communications. Moreover, internal communications are often a reaction to the changing characteristics of the external environment.

08:03.000 --> 08:12.000
Organizations use a variety of means of communication with the external environment. For example, they communicate with consumers through a variety of advertising.

08:12.000 --> 08:22.000
They provide relevant reports to the Tax Inspection. In the sphere of relations with the public, they form their image, carry out some charity activity.

08:23.000 --> 08:30.000
They use their advertising, their raw materials, components, conclude contracts on deliveries with suppliers.

08:31.000 --> 08:38.000
Internal communications are communications between structural units and individual performers.

08:39.000 --> 08:50.000
In the framework of vertical communications, information is transferred from level to level within the organization. At the same time, information can be transmitted both in ascending and in descending.

08:50.000 --> 08:57.000
In the case of descending, information is transmitted from the highest levels to the lowest, playing the role of direct communication.

08:58.000 --> 09:08.000
In the case of ascending, communication from bottom to top performs the function of feedback, informing the managers about the state of affairs at the lower levels.

09:09.000 --> 09:14.000
The organization consists of a large number of units closely interconnected with each other.

09:15.000 --> 09:23.000
The coordination of the activities of all these units, in addition to descending and ascending vertical information, is needed in horizontal communications.

09:24.000 --> 09:31.000
Vertical and horizontal communications are considered to act within the official structure of the organization,

09:32.000 --> 09:40.000
according to the line of formal subordination, formal hierarchy, and also according to the lines of formal subordination of horizontal interaction.

09:41.000 --> 09:48.000
However, informal communications also play an important role within the organization, which act within the informal structure.

09:49.000 --> 09:55.000
Information is transmitted through informal channels much faster than through formal channels.

09:56.000 --> 10:01.000
Often, managers use informal communications for planned information leakage.

10:02.000 --> 10:07.000
The term communication itself appeared in scientific literature at the beginning of the 20th century,

10:08.000 --> 10:17.000
although probably the very first model of communication was proposed by Aristotle, who highlighted such components of the communication process as orator, speech, and audience.

10:18.000 --> 10:24.000
The first to study the communication processes in the organization were the representatives of the School of Science and Management.

10:25.000 --> 10:31.000
In particular, Frederick Taylor developed a rigid organizational structure, which was later improved by Henri Fayol,

10:32.000 --> 10:36.000
which involves a clear interconnection between positions and roles.

10:37.000 --> 10:42.000
This structure only includes vertical and horizontal communications from the managers to subordinates.

10:42.000 --> 10:49.000
That is, such an organization is based on formal, extremely rigid, vertical, and hierarchical communication connections.

10:50.000 --> 10:57.000
Information is transmitted vertically, divided into two types, tasks and the necessary explanation for it.

10:58.000 --> 11:02.000
Taylor called it a lesson, as well as control over the execution of the task.

11:03.000 --> 11:08.000
At the same time, feedback during control is reduced only to a report on the execution of the task.

11:08.000 --> 11:14.000
In general, it can be said that this scientific school did not attach much importance to the communication in the organization.

11:15.000 --> 11:21.000
According to the basic concept of the School of Human Relations, a person is a unique social animal,

11:22.000 --> 11:29.000
therefore, no formalization of organizational processes and a rigid hierarchy of subordinates can be combined with his activity.

11:30.000 --> 11:37.000
On the contrary, horizontal organizational connections of informal nature between members of the organization are of great importance.

11:38.000 --> 11:41.000
These connections should facilitate the functioning of the formal organization

11:42.000 --> 11:46.000
and ensure the unity of the collective and the protection of the integrity of the personality.

11:47.000 --> 11:52.000
However, representatives of the School of Human Relations paid attention to mostly informal communication

11:53.000 --> 11:59.000
between the employees of the organization with different statuses, forgetting about their interaction with the administration,

11:59.000 --> 12:10.000
as well as the flow of business information necessary for the performance of their role duties.

12:11.000 --> 12:18.000
All system theories claim that the connections between the various system units of the organization

12:19.000 --> 12:23.000
are the main point in understanding the essence of its functioning.

12:23.000 --> 12:31.000
For the effective operation of these connections, the most important role is played by the creation, obtaining and processing of information.

12:32.000 --> 12:39.000
Considering the organization as an open system, system theories focus on its interaction with the external environment,

12:40.000 --> 12:46.000
the study of the flow of information coming from other organizations and from social institutions,

12:47.000 --> 12:49.000
such as government, political and public institutions.

12:49.000 --> 12:53.000
Within the framework of system theories, the information flows are analyzed

12:54.000 --> 13:00.000
and the quality of the information presented as formal and informal channels is assessed,

13:01.000 --> 13:06.000
as well as the number of decisions made depending on the actions of the communication system.

13:07.000 --> 13:14.000
The main development of communication theory was achieved relatively recently, since the late 1940s.

13:14.000 --> 13:20.000
It is worth paying attention to the details of those theories that are considered to be classical communication theories.

13:21.000 --> 13:28.000
At the end of the 1940s, at the request of Bell Telecom, the famous American mathematician Claude Shannon

13:29.000 --> 13:31.000
began to develop his model of communication.

13:32.000 --> 13:37.000
The model described five functional and one dysfunctional factors of the communication process.

13:38.000 --> 13:44.000
The functional factor was the source of information, which protects the message,

13:45.000 --> 13:50.000
the sender, which encodes the message into signals, the channel that conducts this message,

13:51.000 --> 13:57.000
the receiver and the destination, where the dysfunctional element was noise.

13:58.000 --> 14:00.000
The model has a technical nature.

14:01.000 --> 14:06.000
The main task of this model is to reduce noise, that is, everything that hinders communication.

14:07.000 --> 14:11.000
The main conclusion of this model is the following.

14:12.000 --> 14:17.000
The inability of the participants of communication to realize that the sent and received message do not always coincide

14:18.000 --> 14:23.000
due to the action of noise is a frequent cause of communication difficulties.

14:24.000 --> 14:31.000
This model was called Shannon-Weaver model and was continued by researcher Melvin DeFleur.

14:32.000 --> 14:35.000
He expanded the original model into a more developed network.

14:36.000 --> 14:43.000
The main drawback of the Shannon-Weaver linear model is the lack of feedback.

14:44.000 --> 14:51.000
Feedback allows the communicator to adapt its message to the communicative channel,

14:51.000 --> 14:54.000
naturally, to increase the efficiency of the transmission of information.

14:55.000 --> 15:01.000
The Shannon-Weaver model was a final overcoming of the simplified interpretation of communication

15:02.000 --> 15:03.000
as a one-sided linear process.

15:04.000 --> 15:07.000
The circular nature of communication is emphasized in this model.

15:08.000 --> 15:13.000
The authors paid attention to the behavior of the main participants of communication,

15:14.000 --> 15:19.000
the sender and the receiver, the main tasks of which are encoding, decoding

15:19.000 --> 15:21.000
and interpretation of the message.

15:22.000 --> 15:28.000
Modern researchers of communication processes represent the process of information exchange as follows.

15:29.000 --> 15:34.000
The sender is the creator of the message, the one who proposes an idea

15:35.000 --> 15:42.000
or creates the information on his own or accumulates the existing information for further transmission,

15:43.000 --> 15:47.000
deciding what significant information can be the subject of the transmission,

15:48.000 --> 15:52.000
how to encode it, which channel to send the information to.

15:53.000 --> 15:56.000
The sender thus begins the process of communication exchange.

15:57.000 --> 16:01.000
The message is the information prepared for the transmission to the receiver,

16:02.000 --> 16:05.000
encoded using symbols, words, special sign symbols,

16:06.000 --> 16:09.000
tone of the message, drawings, gestures, and so on.

16:09.000 --> 16:13.000
In the process of encoding, that is, the transformation of the meaning of the idea into symbols,

16:14.000 --> 16:18.000
problems may arise, the actions of which distort the communication,

16:19.000 --> 16:21.000
reduce the effectiveness of the communication process.

16:22.000 --> 16:26.000
For example, the sender makes a message from symbols that the receiver does not understand,

16:27.000 --> 16:31.000
has not met in his previous experience or interprets incorrectly.

16:32.000 --> 16:35.000
The channel of information transmission is a means of information transmission

16:36.000 --> 16:38.000
or a path, a path of actual transmission of the message.

16:39.000 --> 16:48.000
The understanding and acceptance of the received message depends on the quality of the channel of information transmission

16:49.000 --> 16:57.000
and a lot depends on whether the leader can adjust to the individual system of perception of information by the individual.

16:58.000 --> 17:01.000
At the same time, the following channels of information transmission are different.

17:02.000 --> 17:08.000
Speech channel, transmission of written materials, electronic means of communication, such as computer networks,

17:09.000 --> 17:11.000
video conferences, email.

17:12.000 --> 17:19.000
The receiver is a person or a group or an organization to which information is transmitted

17:20.000 --> 17:22.000
and which interprets or decodes it.

17:23.000 --> 17:26.000
The interpretation of the message of the receiver is not always successful.

17:27.000 --> 17:31.000
Incorrect interpretation is often due to the lack of language,

17:32.000 --> 17:36.000
perception, culture, differences in the interests of the sender or receiver.

17:36.000 --> 17:40.000
Noise is all that distorts the meaning of the message.

17:41.000 --> 17:45.000
This is an element that is actually present in all communications.

17:46.000 --> 17:49.000
At each stage, there are possible noises.

17:50.000 --> 17:54.000
The sources of noise that make it difficult to understand the meaning of the message

17:55.000 --> 17:57.000
are the differences in the perception of information,

17:58.000 --> 18:02.000
which affect the clarity of the meaning when encoding and decoding.

18:03.000 --> 18:09.000
This is a mismatch and a difference in the official status,

18:10.000 --> 18:14.000
that is, a different vision of the goals, tasks of the organization, its units,

18:15.000 --> 18:22.000
and the features of the culture, the features of the language of the sender and the receiver.

18:23.000 --> 18:27.000
The result or effect of communication influence is a change in behavior,

18:27.000 --> 18:30.000
in the state of the receiver of information,

18:31.000 --> 18:35.000
which can be expressed in the change in the knowledge of the receiver,

18:36.000 --> 18:38.000
in the change in his attitudes,

18:39.000 --> 18:42.000
or in the change in the individual actions of the receiver, in his behavior.

18:43.000 --> 18:48.000
A feedback is an operative reaction to what is heard, read or seen.

18:49.000 --> 18:52.000
This is information in a verbal or non-verbal form,

18:53.000 --> 18:55.000
which is sent back to the sender.

18:55.000 --> 18:59.000
It indicates the extent of understanding, the extent of trust in the message,

19:00.000 --> 19:05.000
whether the message is learned or not, whether the receiver agrees with it or not.

19:06.000 --> 19:11.000
A feedback allows the sender not only to know the result of the communication act,

19:12.000 --> 19:15.000
but also to correct the following message for greater understanding,

19:16.000 --> 19:17.000
for greater effect of communication.

19:18.000 --> 19:24.000
In a recent study, an attempt was made to explain the process of choosing

19:25.000 --> 19:27.000
the most effective communication channels.

19:28.000 --> 19:32.000
It turned out that the channels differ in the volume of transmitted information.

19:33.000 --> 19:37.000
The throughput or capacity of the channel is the volume of information

19:38.000 --> 19:42.000
that can be transmitted through this channel during one communication session.

19:43.000 --> 19:48.000
The classification of channels by throughput is presented on slide 15.

19:49.000 --> 19:53.000
Three factors affect the capacity of communication channels.

19:53.000 --> 19:58.000
First of all, it is the ability to process several signals and prompts at the same time.

19:59.000 --> 20:03.000
The second is the ability to provide fast two-way feedback.

20:04.000 --> 20:09.000
And finally, the last factor is the ability to provide a personal approach to communication.

20:10.000 --> 20:15.000
The richest means of communication in terms of these capabilities is personal communication,

20:16.000 --> 20:21.000
because it guarantees direct impact, transmission of multiple information signals

20:21.000 --> 20:25.000
and immediate feedback and, of course, personal approach.

20:26.000 --> 20:31.000
In the case of phone communication, there is no personal contact between the sender and the receiver.

20:32.000 --> 20:35.000
Participants do not perceive the poses, the language of gestures of each other.

20:36.000 --> 20:40.000
However, there is a human voice, and it contains a huge amount of emotional information.

20:41.000 --> 20:45.000
In e-mails, there are usually no visual or verbal prompts,

20:46.000 --> 20:49.000
which increases the likelihood of misunderstanding of these messages.

20:49.000 --> 20:52.000
Realizing the need for channels with more capacity,

20:53.000 --> 20:57.000
managers sometimes use video signals, that is, visual prompts.

20:58.000 --> 21:01.000
Notes and letters can also have a personal approach,

21:02.000 --> 21:04.000
but they cannot provide fast feedback.

21:05.000 --> 21:10.000
Personal communication channels are announcements, ballots, standard computer reports,

21:11.000 --> 21:13.000
are the most capacious.

21:13.000 --> 21:16.000
Their throughput is limited to the greatest extent.

21:17.000 --> 21:21.000
Using them, the sender has no ability to focus on a particular receiver,

21:22.000 --> 21:26.000
transmits minimum information and does not receive feedback.

21:27.000 --> 21:32.000
It is obvious that each communication channel has certain advantages and disadvantages.

21:33.000 --> 21:36.000
Each of them, depending on the type of communication,

21:37.000 --> 21:40.000
can be used to achieve a certain level of efficiency.

21:40.000 --> 21:45.000
The choice of the channel depends on whether the message is ordinary, routine or not.

21:46.000 --> 21:50.000
As a rule, non-standard messages are ambiguous, ambiguous,

21:51.000 --> 21:53.000
associated with some new event,

21:54.000 --> 21:58.000
and there is a very high probability that they may be misunderstood.

21:59.000 --> 22:03.000
Often, they are transmitted in a situation characterized by a lack of time,

22:04.000 --> 22:08.000
and therefore, there is a high probability that the message is not correct.

22:08.000 --> 22:12.000
The most capacious channels allow to effectively convey the complexity of the situation.

22:13.000 --> 22:17.000
On the other hand, routine communication is simple and straightforward.

22:18.000 --> 22:21.000
A routine message contains various data

22:22.000 --> 22:26.000
or simply attaches in a written form the information that the managers have already agreed on.

22:27.000 --> 22:31.000
Such messages can be transmitted through less capacious channels.

22:32.000 --> 22:35.000
To the written form, the message is not very complicated,

22:35.000 --> 22:38.000
and the message is transmitted through less capacious channels.

22:39.000 --> 22:43.000
Writing communication has to be used when the receivers of the message are significantly removed from each other

22:44.000 --> 22:47.000
or when the information has some official nature.

22:48.000 --> 22:53.000
The choice of the channel also depends on whether the manager simply wants to distribute the information

22:54.000 --> 22:57.000
or wants to achieve changes in behavior from the subordinates.

22:58.000 --> 23:03.000
Recommendations for choosing a channel, depending on the purpose of communication, are presented on slide 16.

