23:19.000 --> 23:23.000
We move on to the second topic of our lecture — interpersonal communication.

23:24.000 --> 23:27.000
We will discuss the issue of effectiveness and productivity of communication.

23:28.000 --> 23:34.000
Effective communication takes place in cases when the meaning of the message

23:35.000 --> 23:38.000
and the value perceived by the receiver are practically the same.

23:39.000 --> 23:41.000
Although this should be the goal of any communication,

23:42.000 --> 23:45.000
efficiency is not always achievable.

23:46.000 --> 23:52.000
Even now, when I am talking to you, I am not sure that you understand me exactly as I would like.

23:53.000 --> 23:57.000
My confidence would be much higher if you were sitting in the audience

23:58.000 --> 24:02.000
and could ask some questions, meaning, I could get feedback.

24:02.000 --> 24:05.000
The ability to offer feedback and ask questions

24:06.000 --> 24:10.000
is an important way to improve the effectiveness of communication.

24:11.000 --> 24:17.000
Productive communication takes place in cases when the minimum amount of resources is spent.

24:18.000 --> 24:21.000
For example, time is a very important resource.

24:22.000 --> 24:26.000
Imagine a teacher who individually communicates with each student in the group

24:27.000 --> 24:28.000
about the subject they are studying.

24:28.000 --> 24:29.000
This is almost impossible.

24:30.000 --> 24:31.000
But even if it were so,

24:32.000 --> 24:36.000
communication with you would be too expensive in terms of time.

24:37.000 --> 24:40.000
Productive communication is not always effective.

24:41.000 --> 24:45.000
If the sender sends a message via email about changes in the policy,

24:46.000 --> 24:51.000
it can save him time, but not always lead to a positive result,

24:52.000 --> 24:54.000
that is, to the desired interpretation and response.

24:55.000 --> 24:59.000
Similarly, effective communication is not always productive.

25:00.000 --> 25:03.000
If the production manager personally approaches each worker

25:04.000 --> 25:06.000
and explains all the changes in the procedure to him,

25:07.000 --> 25:09.000
it can guarantee that everyone will understand it correctly.

25:10.000 --> 25:14.000
However, this will be unacceptable and expensive in terms of time.

25:15.000 --> 25:17.000
Effective communication between managers and other people

25:18.000 --> 25:24.000
implies the need to use all the elements presented in the communication model.

25:25.000 --> 25:31.000
If the sender or receiver is unable to encode or decode the message in a similar way,

25:32.000 --> 25:34.000
the communication process is interrupted.

25:35.000 --> 25:39.000
The choice of the channel also largely determines the interference resistance of the messages.

25:40.000 --> 25:46.000
The ability of both parties to listen depends on whether the message is correctly perceived and received.

25:47.000 --> 25:51.000
Thus, effective communication requires the knowledge of the interpersonal factors

25:52.000 --> 25:55.000
that influence the communication process from the manager,

25:56.000 --> 25:59.000
such as channels of communication, non-verbal behavior,

26:00.000 --> 26:03.000
the ability to listen, the ability to provide high-quality feedback.

26:04.000 --> 26:06.000
In the process of interpersonal communication,

26:07.000 --> 26:11.000
information can be presented in a verbal, paraverbal and non-verbal form.

26:12.000 --> 26:17.000
If verbal communications are directly related to the content of the transmitted information,

26:18.000 --> 26:24.000
then paraverbal and nonverbal communications demonstrate the attitude of the interlocutors to it

26:25.000 --> 26:29.000
and thus largely determine the effectiveness of the information assimilation to its addressee.

26:30.000 --> 26:34.000
It is believed that from the total flow of information

26:35.000 --> 26:37.000
that a person perceives in the process of communication,

26:37.000 --> 26:42.000
up to 80% is non-verbal and paraverbal information,

26:43.000 --> 26:46.000
and only up to 20% is the words themselves.

26:47.000 --> 26:49.000
The use of psychotechnologies,

26:50.000 --> 26:55.000
originally developed in psychotherapy and intended to increase the degree of influence on the interlocutor,

26:56.000 --> 26:59.000
sharply increases the productivity of interpersonal communication.

27:00.000 --> 27:02.000
You can get acquainted with such technologies

27:03.000 --> 27:05.000
during the study of the course on the psychology of business communication.

27:05.000 --> 27:08.000
We only focus on those communication barriers

27:09.000 --> 27:11.000
that arise in the process of interpersonal interaction.

27:12.000 --> 27:15.000
It is very important to remember about the seven sources of noise

27:16.000 --> 27:19.000
that are most often encountered in interpersonal communication.

27:20.000 --> 27:22.000
First of all, this is the inability to listen to the interlocutor,

27:23.000 --> 27:24.000
this is physical distortion,

27:25.000 --> 27:26.000
this is semantic problems,

27:27.000 --> 27:28.000
this is mixed messages,

27:29.000 --> 27:30.000
cultural differences

27:31.000 --> 27:32.000
and the absence of feedback,

27:33.000 --> 27:34.000
as well as the effects of status.

27:35.000 --> 27:38.000
Those who are able to listen understand the skills of receiving messages,

27:39.000 --> 27:44.000
to highlight the facts and feelings contained in them,

27:45.000 --> 27:46.000
and to correctly interpret their meaning.

27:47.000 --> 27:49.000
Only then does the manager have the opportunity

27:50.000 --> 27:51.000
to adequately respond to the original message.

27:52.000 --> 27:56.000
The ability to listen requires attention from a person,

27:57.000 --> 27:59.000
energy expenditure, and a certain experience.

28:00.000 --> 28:04.000
Listening is 75% of effective communication.

28:05.000 --> 28:10.000
At the same time, most people spend only 30 or 40% of their communication time on it.

28:11.000 --> 28:13.000
This leads to numerous communication errors.

28:14.000 --> 28:18.000
Many people do not know how to listen to their interlocutors.

28:19.000 --> 28:21.000
They are concerned, first of all, about what they will say,

28:22.000 --> 28:23.000
not what they are told.

28:24.000 --> 28:25.000
Our ability to listen,

28:26.000 --> 28:28.000
expressed in the volume of understood and memorized material,

28:29.000 --> 28:30.000
on average does not exceed 25%.

28:31.000 --> 28:33.000
A person who can listen to an interlocutor

28:33.000 --> 28:35.000
finds interesting topics in conversation,

28:36.000 --> 28:37.000
conducts a conversation flexibly,

28:38.000 --> 28:40.000
summarizes the received information in a thoughtful way,

28:41.000 --> 28:44.000
evaluates and predicts the information

28:45.000 --> 28:46.000
that he will receive in the next minute.

28:47.000 --> 28:49.000
The correct approach to listening suggests

28:50.000 --> 28:51.000
that you do not think about yourself,

28:52.000 --> 28:54.000
but empathize, participate emotionally in the dialogue,

28:55.000 --> 28:57.000
and penetrate the feelings of the interlocutor.

28:58.000 --> 29:02.000
Therefore, a certain level of development of emotional abilities is necessary for this.

29:03.000 --> 29:04.000
This is called empathy.

29:05.000 --> 29:07.000
As an example of a sample listener,

29:08.000 --> 29:10.000
we can give some talk show presenters.

29:11.000 --> 29:14.000
For example, the famous TV presenter Vladimir Molchanov

29:15.000 --> 29:16.000
actively listens to guests in the studio.

29:17.000 --> 29:18.000
He does not allow himself to be distracted,

29:19.000 --> 29:20.000
he concentrates all his attention on the speakers.

29:21.000 --> 29:22.000
He establishes eye contact,

29:23.000 --> 29:24.000
he listens with empathy,

29:25.000 --> 29:26.000
he participates emotionally in the conversation.

29:27.000 --> 29:29.000
He never interrupts the interlocutor

29:30.000 --> 29:32.000
and at the end rephrases the statement of the interlocutor.

29:33.000 --> 29:36.000
In order to make sure that he understood him correctly.

29:37.000 --> 29:39.000
Thanks to Vladimir Molchanov's developed ability to listen,

29:40.000 --> 29:43.000
his guests feel themselves desirable, understood and significant.

29:44.000 --> 29:46.000
Compare this talk show, let them say,

29:47.000 --> 29:49.000
where the presenter does not have the skills of listening.

29:50.000 --> 29:52.000
Any number of physical distortions

29:53.000 --> 29:55.000
can also reduce the effectiveness of communication.

29:56.000 --> 29:58.000
It is necessary to exclude such interference as

29:59.000 --> 30:02.000
phone calls, random visitors, the arrival of a secretary.

30:03.000 --> 30:06.000
Semantic communication barriers include

30:07.000 --> 30:10.000
a bad choice of words or improper use of them.

30:11.000 --> 30:13.000
In general, semantics studies the ways of using words

30:14.000 --> 30:16.000
and the meanings given by words.

30:17.000 --> 30:20.000
Since words or symbols can have different meanings for different people,

30:21.000 --> 30:23.000
what someone is going to say

30:24.000 --> 30:26.000
will not necessarily be interpreted and understood

30:27.000 --> 30:29.000
in the same way by the recipient of information.

30:29.000 --> 30:31.000
The full dictionary of English

30:32.000 --> 30:34.000
provides more than 14,000 possible definitions

30:35.000 --> 30:37.000
for 500 most common words.

30:38.000 --> 30:40.000
A leader who tells a subordinate

30:41.000 --> 30:43.000
that the report is adequate

30:44.000 --> 30:46.000
may mean that it is complete and meets the goals.

30:47.000 --> 30:49.000
However, a subordinate can decode it in a different way.

30:50.000 --> 30:53.000
For example, he can understand that the report is incomplete

30:54.000 --> 30:57.000
or needs improvement or is out of order.

30:57.000 --> 31:00.000
Studies have shown that managers and leaders of different levels

31:01.000 --> 31:04.000
give the same meaning to words such as status,

31:05.000 --> 31:09.000
incentive, quota, cooperation, budget, and other words.

31:10.000 --> 31:13.000
Semantic difficulties can also be caused

31:14.000 --> 31:16.000
by the divergence of the ways

31:17.000 --> 31:20.000
by which people assign meanings to groups of symbols.

31:21.000 --> 31:24.000
This moment is of great importance for communication.

31:24.000 --> 31:26.000
For example, if you tell your subordinate

31:27.000 --> 31:30.000
to do something as soon as you are given the opportunity,

31:31.000 --> 31:33.000
what do you really mean?

31:34.000 --> 31:36.000
As soon as possible or as soon as you have time?

31:37.000 --> 31:40.000
Semantic barriers can create communication problems

31:41.000 --> 31:43.000
for companies operating in a multinational environment.

31:44.000 --> 31:47.000
Another problem is overloading of the message.

31:48.000 --> 31:51.000
Overloading can be caused by an abundance of professional terms

31:51.000 --> 31:54.000
and expressions that are not always understood

31:55.000 --> 31:58.000
by employees of other departments or other organizations.

31:59.000 --> 32:01.000
Complex language obscures people's consciousness,

32:02.000 --> 32:05.000
and great strategic ideas are almost always described in short words,

32:06.000 --> 32:08.000
as Jack Trout said.

32:09.000 --> 32:13.000
When there is a doubt about the clarity of a written or oral message,

32:14.000 --> 32:18.000
Trout advised to remember the well-known principle of kiss communication.

32:18.000 --> 32:20.000
Keep it short and smile.

32:21.000 --> 32:23.000
We are talking about mixed messages,

32:24.000 --> 32:26.000
in those cases when words convey one message,

32:27.000 --> 32:29.000
and the body language is different.

32:30.000 --> 32:32.000
It is very important to follow the body language,

32:33.000 --> 32:36.000
because non-verbal symbols are able to give a key to understanding

32:37.000 --> 32:40.000
what should actually be said during a personal conversation.

32:41.000 --> 32:44.000
They highlight three sources of information signals

32:45.000 --> 32:47.000
that are transmitted in a decent communication.

32:48.000 --> 32:50.000
These are the words that are spoken,

32:51.000 --> 32:53.000
the voice, i.e. the tension of the voice, intonation, tone,

32:54.000 --> 32:56.000
and the expression of the person-interlocutor.

32:57.000 --> 32:59.000
As for the weight of these three factors

33:00.000 --> 33:02.000
when interpreting messages,

33:03.000 --> 33:07.000
verbal impact is 7% of the total amount of communication,

33:08.000 --> 33:10.000
voice is 38%,

33:11.000 --> 33:15.000
and the expression of the person is 55% of the total amount of received information.

33:15.000 --> 33:18.000
It is obvious that it is not important what is said,

33:19.000 --> 33:21.000
but how it is said, how words are pronounced.

33:22.000 --> 33:25.000
Non-verbal messages convey thoughts and feelings

33:26.000 --> 33:29.000
much more effectively than any of the most carefully selected words.

33:30.000 --> 33:35.000
And all verbal and non-verbal messages can contradict each other.

33:36.000 --> 33:38.000
In this case, the recipient comes to a confusion.

33:39.000 --> 33:41.000
What did the person want to say?

33:42.000 --> 33:44.000
To what extent should we trust his words,

33:45.000 --> 33:46.000
his behavior?

33:47.000 --> 33:49.000
Studies show that non-verbal symbols are usually trusted.

33:50.000 --> 33:51.000
Cultural differences.

33:52.000 --> 33:54.000
In the conditions of globalization, for many companies,

33:55.000 --> 33:57.000
moving employees within the framework of the international office

33:58.000 --> 34:00.000
becomes one of the main principles of work.

34:01.000 --> 34:05.000
This helps to educate leaders who can manage international business.

34:06.000 --> 34:09.000
However, often the results shown by a manager in one country

34:10.000 --> 34:12.000
can be completely different in another country.

34:12.000 --> 34:14.000
It can be not so effective.

34:15.000 --> 34:17.000
This is due to national features,

34:18.000 --> 34:20.000
various ways of doing business,

34:21.000 --> 34:23.000
and culture and relations between people in different countries.

34:24.000 --> 34:27.000
Under the influence of culture, relations to work are formed,

34:28.000 --> 34:33.000
relations to time, to their colleagues, to goals, to lifestyle.

34:34.000 --> 34:38.000
These values ​​have a huge importance for a successful business of a company.

34:38.000 --> 34:42.000
For example, Americans are considered to be big individualists.

34:43.000 --> 34:44.000
They are independent and independent.

34:45.000 --> 34:47.000
Their motivation is based solely on personal benefit.

34:48.000 --> 34:51.000
Their success is measured by the amount of money.

34:52.000 --> 34:55.000
Therefore, they save time, they value punctuality,

34:56.000 --> 34:57.000
they live on schedule.

34:58.000 --> 35:01.000
Representatives of courageous cultures, such as Japan, Germany, America,

35:02.000 --> 35:03.000
are aimed at achieving results.

35:04.000 --> 35:05.000
They are ready for competition.

35:06.000 --> 35:07.000
They are aggressive in their business.

35:08.000 --> 35:11.000
Women's cultures, such as Russia, Ukraine or the Baltic States,

35:12.000 --> 35:16.000
consider work not as a goal, but as a means of comfort.

35:17.000 --> 35:20.000
Excessive control by the company management

35:21.000 --> 35:23.000
will be perceived by the Western manager as a sign of distrust.

35:24.000 --> 35:26.000
On the contrary, representing the complete freedom of action

35:27.000 --> 35:28.000
to an employee from Russia or Ukraine,

35:29.000 --> 35:31.000
the manager risks not to get any results.

35:32.000 --> 35:34.000
Another example of the influence of cultural features

35:34.000 --> 35:39.000
is the process of merging the German Daimler company with the American Chrysler.

35:40.000 --> 35:42.000
As a result, the joint company had problems

35:43.000 --> 35:44.000
that initially seemed unimportant.

35:45.000 --> 35:48.000
For Germans who are used to smoking and drinking beer for lunch,

35:49.000 --> 35:53.000
and Americans who lead a more British lifestyle,

35:54.000 --> 35:57.000
it was necessary to create certain rules of conduct in the office

35:58.000 --> 36:00.000
that would be comfortable for all participants in the process.

36:01.000 --> 36:04.000
Today, international standards of business communication

36:05.000 --> 36:07.000
developed by the World Trade Association have been adopted.

36:08.000 --> 36:12.000
The standards include the rules of conduct in the business environment,

36:13.000 --> 36:15.000
the rules of business negotiations,

36:16.000 --> 36:17.000
the rules of reception,

36:18.000 --> 36:19.000
the handover of protocol gifts, and so on.

36:20.000 --> 36:21.000
In the context of globalization,

36:22.000 --> 36:24.000
these standards significantly facilitate intercultural communication

36:25.000 --> 36:27.000
and allow to avoid many conflict situations.

36:27.000 --> 36:29.000
The study of the specified standards

36:30.000 --> 36:32.000
is included in almost all training programs

36:33.000 --> 36:36.000
for preparing managers for foreign economic activity.

36:37.000 --> 36:39.000
International business experts advise

36:40.000 --> 36:42.000
to study the language of the country where you are going

36:43.000 --> 36:47.000
at least in a minimal volume for a better understanding of cultural differences,

36:48.000 --> 36:50.000
with the representatives of which you plan to have a business.

36:51.000 --> 36:55.000
Perhaps the prospect of studying a foreign language may sound frightening,

36:55.000 --> 36:59.000
but the results are quite justified by the efforts made.

37:00.000 --> 37:02.000
The feedback allows the manager to determine

37:03.000 --> 37:06.000
how effective or ineffective his communication is.

37:07.000 --> 37:09.000
We have already talked about the possibility of feedback

37:10.000 --> 37:12.000
when we talked about the communication model.

37:13.000 --> 37:15.000
But despite all the significance,

37:16.000 --> 37:19.000
feedback is often not paid enough attention to,

37:20.000 --> 37:22.000
and in the process of interpersonal communication

37:22.000 --> 37:25.000
feedback requires special attention.

37:26.000 --> 37:29.000
Feedback is a deliberate message to another person

37:30.000 --> 37:33.000
about the actions that lead to the achievement of the goal

37:34.000 --> 37:39.000
and those that lead to the results that do not meet the goals of the organization.

37:40.000 --> 37:43.000
Feedback functions are support and encouragement of actions

37:44.000 --> 37:46.000
that lead to success and give the desired result,

37:47.000 --> 37:49.000
or change of ineffective behavior.

37:49.000 --> 37:52.000
The ability to provide both positive and negative feedback

37:53.000 --> 37:57.000
is a necessary component of the effective leader's communicative competence.

37:58.000 --> 38:01.000
It is appropriate to provide feedback to subordinates

38:02.000 --> 38:04.000
in accordance with the following principles.

38:05.000 --> 38:07.000
Feedback should be balanced.

38:08.000 --> 38:10.000
If feedback is too critical,

38:11.000 --> 38:13.000
the subordinate may internally reject it.

38:14.000 --> 38:16.000
If feedback is too praiseworthy,

38:16.000 --> 38:19.000
it may be perceived as protection, which will also cause a negative effect.

38:20.000 --> 38:24.000
Feedback should combine positive and negative points.

38:25.000 --> 38:30.000
Balancing should be done in order to make feedback acceptable for the subordinate

38:31.000 --> 38:35.000
depending on his nationality, culture, and personal characteristics.

38:36.000 --> 38:37.000
Feedback should be specific.

38:38.000 --> 38:40.000
Feedback is not a place for discussion

38:41.000 --> 38:44.000
whether the subordinate said or did something.

38:44.000 --> 38:48.000
The leader should always address a specific fact or action.

38:49.000 --> 38:52.000
Avoid generalizing phrases such as

38:53.000 --> 38:54.000
«you are always», «you are inclined».

38:55.000 --> 38:58.000
Feedback is about what was done or said,

38:59.000 --> 39:00.000
how and why.

39:01.000 --> 39:03.000
Guesses about someone's motives

39:04.000 --> 39:06.000
bring an atmosphere of distrust and hostility into communication.

39:07.000 --> 39:08.000
Feedback should be understandable.

39:09.000 --> 39:12.000
The leader should use a language understandable for the subordinate,

39:12.000 --> 39:15.000
without jargon and unfamiliar words.

39:16.000 --> 39:18.000
Feedback should be active.

39:19.000 --> 39:21.000
The subordinate should not remain a passive listener.

39:22.000 --> 39:25.000
He should be actively involved in the process of changing his behavior

39:26.000 --> 39:27.000
to achieve certain tasks.

39:28.000 --> 39:30.000
In order to make the feedback process more active,

39:31.000 --> 39:33.000
it is useful to ask the subordinate himself,

39:34.000 --> 39:35.000
to make comments about his behavior,

39:36.000 --> 39:38.000
about his knowledge or about his skills.

39:39.000 --> 39:40.000
Feedback should be comparable.

39:40.000 --> 39:43.000
Progress is made if the subordinate can compare

39:44.000 --> 39:45.000
how he performed a specific task

39:46.000 --> 39:48.000
with his previous attempts.

39:49.000 --> 39:52.000
Feedback should be directed at behavior.

39:53.000 --> 39:55.000
Feedback focuses attention on behavior,

39:56.000 --> 39:57.000
not on the Personality as such.

39:58.000 --> 40:00.000
You should talk about what people do,

40:01.000 --> 40:02.000
not what you think about them.

40:03.000 --> 40:04.000
Thus, you can tell someone

40:05.000 --> 40:06.000
that he spoke the most at the meeting,

40:07.000 --> 40:09.000
instead of saying «you are too talkative».

40:10.000 --> 40:12.000
The first phrase leaves room for change in behavior,

40:13.000 --> 40:16.000
while the second phrase simply states that he is talkative,

40:17.000 --> 40:20.000
emphasizes a certain feature of his character.

40:21.000 --> 40:22.000
Feedback should be sufficient.

40:23.000 --> 40:24.000
When a person performs his work,

40:25.000 --> 40:26.000
he makes some efforts and tries.

40:27.000 --> 40:30.000
Therefore, if he receives some kind of fleeting feedback,

40:31.000 --> 40:33.000
especially in the case of a long-awaited achievement,

40:34.000 --> 40:35.000
he may have a feeling

40:36.000 --> 40:37.000
that his efforts were unnoticed.

40:37.000 --> 40:40.000
This can lead to demotivation of an employee.

40:41.000 --> 40:43.000
The so-called Russell feedback formula

40:44.000 --> 40:46.000
has been widely spread.

40:47.000 --> 40:48.000
According to it,

40:49.000 --> 40:51.000
the supervisor should follow this algorithm

40:52.000 --> 40:54.000
in the process of presenting feedback to an employee.

40:55.000 --> 40:57.000
First of all, let the employee see

40:58.000 --> 41:00.000
what he did on specific facts.

41:01.000 --> 41:03.000
Show him the consequences of this behavior

41:04.000 --> 41:08.000
and outline further actions to change this behavior.

41:09.000 --> 41:13.000
Depending on the situation and personal characteristics,

41:14.000 --> 41:16.000
people differ in the fact

41:17.000 --> 41:19.000
that they can receive a different number of feedback.

41:20.000 --> 41:23.000
Each critical word is a drop that gets into a certain vessel.

41:24.000 --> 41:25.000
If you listen carefully and actively,

41:26.000 --> 41:29.000
you can understand that this vessel is approaching its fullness.

41:30.000 --> 41:32.000
If a person is willing to receive a comment,

41:33.000 --> 41:34.000
he says,

41:35.000 --> 41:36.000
«Yes, now I see it, I know,

41:37.000 --> 41:39.000
I would like to hear even more comments».

41:40.000 --> 41:42.000
If the vessel is close to its fullness,

41:43.000 --> 41:44.000
you can hear such comments.

41:45.000 --> 41:47.000
«I think I don't understand», «No, I didn't do that»,

41:48.000 --> 41:49.000
«Maybe yes, maybe no».

41:50.000 --> 41:51.000
This means that feedback should be stopped

41:52.000 --> 41:55.000
and waited for when a person will learn what you have said.

41:56.000 --> 41:58.000
Status and differences in existing organizations

41:59.000 --> 42:01.000
create potential communication barriers

42:01.000 --> 42:02.000
between people of different ranks.

42:03.000 --> 42:06.000
On the one hand, using the power of one's own status,

42:07.000 --> 42:09.000
managers may be inclined to talk a lot and listen little.

42:10.000 --> 42:12.000
On the other hand, communication is often distorted

42:13.000 --> 42:14.000
when there is a rising flow

42:15.000 --> 42:16.000
in the hierarchical structure of the organization.

42:17.000 --> 42:19.000
Subordinates can filter information

42:20.000 --> 42:22.000
and tell their leader only what,

42:23.000 --> 42:24.000
in their opinion, they would like to hear.

42:25.000 --> 42:26.000
No matter what the reason is,

42:27.000 --> 42:30.000
fear of retribution for bad news

42:31.000 --> 42:32.000
or a desire to admit one's mistakes

42:33.000 --> 42:35.000
or a general mood to do something pleasant,

42:36.000 --> 42:38.000
as it always leads to the same result.

42:39.000 --> 42:41.000
That is, a person who makes decisions at a high level

42:42.000 --> 42:44.000
can make mistakes

42:45.000 --> 42:47.000
due to distortion or inaccurate information

42:48.000 --> 42:49.000
that came from below.

42:50.000 --> 42:51.000
To avoid such problems,

42:52.000 --> 42:53.000
managers and group leaders

42:54.000 --> 42:55.000
should build trustworthy working relations

42:56.000 --> 42:57.000
with subordinates and members of the group,

42:57.000 --> 43:00.000
taking all the advantages of communication face to face.

43:01.000 --> 43:02.000
Currently, the most popular way

43:03.000 --> 43:06.000
to build trust is the management of walking methods.

43:07.000 --> 43:08.000
This method means

43:09.000 --> 43:12.000
that the leader should only regularly leave his office

43:13.000 --> 43:15.000
and talk to people at work.

43:16.000 --> 43:18.000
Managers who spend a lot of time this way

43:19.000 --> 43:20.000
significantly reduce the distance

43:21.000 --> 43:23.000
between themselves and their subordinates.

43:24.000 --> 43:25.000
This helps to create an atmosphere of open

43:25.000 --> 43:27.000
and free communication between people,

43:28.000 --> 43:30.000
regardless of their official position.

43:31.000 --> 43:32.000
As a result, when making decisions,

43:33.000 --> 43:35.000
the leader has more information at his disposal,

43:36.000 --> 43:37.000
and at the same time decisions

43:38.000 --> 43:39.000
meet the needs of the workers.

43:40.000 --> 43:43.000
What is the role of communication in the organization?

43:44.000 --> 43:46.000
We move on to another aspect of communication

43:47.000 --> 43:48.000
related to the organization as a whole.

43:49.000 --> 43:50.000
On the organization scale,

43:51.000 --> 43:53.000
communication is usually carried out in three directions.

43:53.000 --> 43:54.000
From top to bottom, from bottom to top,

43:55.000 --> 43:56.000
and in a horizontal plane.

43:57.000 --> 43:59.000
Information in the organization

44:00.000 --> 44:03.000
is distributed both on formal and informal channels.

44:04.000 --> 44:08.000
Formal channels coincide with the hierarchical levels in the organization.

44:09.000 --> 44:11.000
The organizational structure determines

44:12.000 --> 44:14.000
which way the official information,

44:15.000 --> 44:16.000
the official message,

44:17.000 --> 44:19.000
should go from one hierarchical level to another.

44:19.000 --> 44:23.000
Since formal channels are recognized as official,

44:24.000 --> 44:26.000
